'''Communicative competence''' is a term in [[linguistics]] which refers to a language user's grammatical  knowledge of [[syntax]], [[Morphology (linguistics)|morphology]], [[phonology]] and the like, as well as social knowledge about how and when to use utterances appropriately.

The term was coined by [[Dell Hymes]] in 1966,{{sfn|Hymes|1966}} reacting against the perceived inadequacy of [[Noam Chomsky]]'s (1965) distinction between ''[[linguistic competence]]'' and ''[[Linguistic performance|performance]]''.{{sfn|Chomsky|1965}} To address Chomsky's abstract notion of competence, Hymes undertook [[ethnographic]] exploration of communicative competence that included "communicative form and function in integral relation to each other".{{sfn|Leung|2005}} The approach pioneered by Hymes is now known as the [[ethnography of communication]].

The notion of communicative competence is one of the theories that underlies the [[Communicative language teaching|communicative approach]] to foreign language teaching.{{sfn|Leung|2005}} At least three core models exist. The first and most widely used is Canale and Swain's model{{sfn|Canale|Swain|1980}} and the later iteration by Canale.{{sfn|Canale|1983}} In a second model, sociocultural content is more precisely specified by Celce-Murcia, Dornyei, and Thurrell in 1995. For their part, they saw communicative competence as including linguistic competence, strategic competence, sociocultural competence, actional competence, and discourse competence.{{sfn|Celce-Murcia|Dornyei|Thurrell|1995}} A third model widely in use in federal language training in Canada is Bachman and Palmer's model.{{sfn|Bachman|Palmer|2010}}

The understanding of communicative competence has been influenced by the field of [[pragmatics]] and the [[philosophy of language]], including work on [[speech act]]s.{{sfn|Hymes|1964}}
