{{redirect|FMNH|the Florida Museum of Natural History|FLMNH}} {{Infobox Museum |name = The Field Museum |image = Field Museum of Natural History.jpg |alt = |imagesize = | map_type = Chicago#Illinois#USA |map_caption = Location in Chicago |coordinates = {{coord|41.866110|-87.616940|display=inline}} |established = 1893 |location = 1400 S. [[Lake Shore Drive]], [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States |visitors = 1,650,000 (2016)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aecom.com/content/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/2016-ThemeMuseum-Index.pdf |title=TEA-AECOM 2016 Theme Index and Museum Index: The Global Attractions Attendance Report |pages=68–73 |publisher=[[Themed Entertainment Association]] |accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref> |director = |publictransit = |website = {{url|www.fieldmuseum.org}}
{{Infobox NRHP |name =Field Museum of Natural History |embed=yes | image = | caption = | location= | locmapin = | map_caption = | area = | built =1921 | architect = [[William Peirce Anderson]] of [[Graham, Anderson, Probst & White]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Architecture |url=http://www.fieldmuseum.org/about/history/architecture |website=The Field Museum |access-date=September 11, 2015}}</ref> | architecture= [[Neoclassicism|Classical Revival]] | added = September 5, 1975 | governing_body = Private | refnum=75000647<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref> }} }}
The '''Field Museum of Natural History''', also known as '''The Field Museum''', is a [[natural history museum]] in the city of [[Chicago]], and is one of the largest such museums in the world.<ref name=Bardoe>{{cite book|last=Bardoe|first=Cheryl|title=The Field Museum|year=2011|publisher=Beckon Books}}</ref> The museum maintains its status as a premier [[natural history]] museum through the size and quality of its educational and scientific programs,<ref name=Coleman /><ref name=Williams1973>{{cite book|last=Williams|first=PM|title=Museums of Natural History and the people who work in them|year=1973|publisher=St. Martin’s Press|location=New York}}</ref> as well as due to its extensive scientific specimen and artifact collections.<ref name="Boyer 1993" /> The diverse, high quality permanent exhibitions,<ref name=Metzler2007>{{cite book|last=Metzler|first=S|title=Theatres of Nature Dioramas at the Field Museum.|year=2007|publisher=Field Museum of Natural History|location=Chicago}}</ref> which attract up to two million visitors annually, range from the earliest fossils to past and current cultures from around the world to interactive programming demonstrating today's urgent [[conservation (ethic)|conservation]] needs.<ref name=MIP>{{cite web|title=Museums in the Park: Attendance Statistics|url=http://www.museumsinthepark.org/}}</ref><ref name=Alexander /> It is named in honor of its first major benefactor, [[Marshall Field]].
Additionally, the Field Museum maintains a temporary exhibition program of traveling shows as well as in-house produced topical exhibitions.<ref name="FM Traveling">{{cite web|title=Field Museum Traveling Exhibitions|url=http://fieldmuseum.org/about/traveling-exhibitions}}</ref> The professional staff maintains collections of over 24 million specimens and objects that provide the basis for the museum’s scientific research programs.<ref name=Bardoe /><ref name="Boyer 1993">{{cite book|last=Boyer|first=BH|title=The Natural History of the Field Museum: Exploring the Earth and its People|year=1993|publisher=Field Museum|location=Chicago}}</ref><ref name=Nitecki /> These collections include the full range of existing biodiversity, gems, meteorites, fossils, as well as rich anthropological collections and cultural artifacts from around the globe.<ref name="Boyer 1993" /><ref name="Shopland & Breslaur">{{cite book|last=Shopland|first=JM and L Breslauer|title=The Anthropology Collections of the Field Museum|year=1998|publisher=The Field Museum|location=Chicago}}</ref><ref name="Resetar & Voris">{{cite book|last=Resetar|first=A and HK Voris|title=Herpetology at the Field Museum of Natural History, Chicago: the First Hundred Years|year=1997|publisher=American Society of Ichthyologists and Herpetologists|location=Lawrence, Kansas}}</ref><ref name=Lowther1995>{{cite book|last=Lowther, P 1995. |title=Ornithology at the Field Museum, pp145-161. In: Davis, W.E. Jr. and J.A. Jackson (eds). Contributions to the History of North American Ornithology. Memoirs of the Nuttall Ornithological Club, 12, Cambridge, Massachusetts.}}</ref> The Field Museum Library, which contains over 275,000 books, journals, and photo archives focused on biological systematics, evolutionary biology, geology, archaeology, ethnology and material culture, supports the Field Museum’s academic research faculty and exhibit development.<ref name="Williams & Fawcett">{{cite journal |last1=Williams |first1=Benjamin W. |last2=Fawcett |first2=W. Peyton |title=Field Museum of Natural History Library |date=1985 |journal=Science and Technology Libraries |volume=6 |issue=1/2 |pages=27–34 |doi=10.1300/J122v06n01_04}}</ref>
The Field Museum academic faculty and scientific staff engage in field expeditions, in biodiversity and cultural research on all continents, in local and foreign student training, in stewardship of the rich specimen and artifact collections, and work in close collaboration with public programming exhibitions and education initiatives.<ref name=Nitecki /><ref name="NashFeinman">{{cite book|last=Nash|first=S. E.|title=Curators, collections, and contexts: Anthropology at the Field Museum, 1893–2002|year=2003|publisher=Field Museum of Natural History|location=Chicago|author2=GM Feinman}}</ref><ref name=CEB>{{cite web|title=CEB, Committee on Evolutionary Biology, University of Chicago, Faculty (Field Museum)|url=http://evbio.uchicago.edu/people/faculty/}}</ref><ref name=UIC>{{cite web|title=University of Illinois at Chicago, Department of Anthropology, Associated Field Museum Faculty|url=http://anthropology.las.uic.edu/anthropology/people/associated-field-museum-faculty}}</ref>
==History== [[File:Annual report of the Director to the Board of Trustees for the year .. (1906) (17809550884).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Stanley Field, Field Museum President, 1906]] The Field Museum and its collections originated from the 1893 [[World’s Columbian Exposition]] and the artifacts displayed at the fair.<ref name="WDL">{{cite web |url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/2518/ |title = Port of Aden from the Sea |website = [[World Digital Library]] |date = December 1894 |accessdate = 2013-06-11 }}</ref>{{better source|date=January 2017}} In order to house the exhibits and collections assembled for the 1893 Chicago World’s Fair for future generations, [[Edward Ayer]] convinced the merchant [[Marshall Field]] to fund the establishment of a museum.<ref name=Lockwood>{{cite book|last=Lockwood|first=F.C.|title=The life of Edward E. Ayer.|year=1929|publisher=AC McClurg|location=Chicago, IL}}</ref> Originally titled the ''Columbian Museum of Chicago'' in honor of its origins, the Field Museum was incorporated by the State of Illinois on September 16, 1893, for the purpose of the "accumulation and dissemination of knowledge, and the preservation and exhibition of artifacts illustrating art, archaeology, science and history."<ref name="Farrington1930">{{cite journal|last=Farrington|first=OC|title=A Brief History of Field Museum from 1893 to 1930|journal=Field Museum News|year=1930|volume=1|issue=1|pages=1, 3|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/4376562}}</ref> The Columbian Museum of Chicago occupied the only building remaining from the World's Columbian Exposition in Jackson Park, the Palace of Fine Arts, which now houses the [[Museum of Science and Industry (Chicago)|Museum of Science and Industry]].<ref name="Alexander">{{cite book|last=Alexander|first=EP|title=Museums in Motion: An Introduction to the History and Functions of Museums|year=1979|publisher=American Association for State and Local History|location=Nashville}}</ref>
In 1905, the museum's name was changed from Columbian Museum of Chicago to ''Field Museum of Natural History'' to honor its first major benefactor, Marshall Field, and to reflect its focus on the natural sciences.<ref name="Annual Report">{{cite journal|last=Field Museum of Natural History|title=Annual Report of the Director to the Board of Trustees for the Year 1906|year=1907|volume=3|issue=1|pages=8–9|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/4350936}}</ref> During the period from 1943<ref>{{cite book|last=Field|first=S.|title=Address of Mr. Stanley Field, president of the Museum|year=1943|publisher=Field Museum Press|location=Chicago|pages=3–5}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Field|first=S.|title=Fifty years of progress|journal=Field Museum News|year=1943|volume=14|issue=9/10|pages=3–10}}</ref> to 1966,<ref name=webber66>{{cite journal|last=Webber|first=EL|title=Field Museum Again: name change honors Field Family|journal=Field Museum of Natural History Bulletin|year=1966|volume=37|issue=3|pages=2–3|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/4188067#page/2/mode/1up}}</ref> the museum was known as the Chicago Natural History Museum. In 1921, the Museum moved from its original location in [[Jackson Park (Chicago)|Jackson Park]] to its present site on Chicago Park District property near downtown.<ref>{{cite web|title=Field Museum Changes Locations|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/field_museum_library/sets/72157614806438040/}}</ref> By the late 1930s the Field emerged as one of the three premier museums in the United States, the other two being the American Museum of Natural History (AMNH, New York) and the National Museum of Natural History (Smithsonian Institution, Washington DC).<ref name=Coleman>{{cite book|last=Coleman|first=LV|title=The Museums in America: A critical study, Volumes 1-3.|year=1939|publisher=The American Association of Museums}}</ref>
The Field Museum has maintained its reputation through continuous growth, expanding the scope of collections and its scientific research output, in addition to the its award-winning exhibitions, outreach publications, and programs.<ref name=Williams1973 /><ref name=Nitecki>{{cite journal|last=Nitecki|first=M|title=Field Museum of Natural History|journal=ASC Newsletter|year=1980|volume=8|issue=5|pages=61–70}}</ref><ref name=NashFeinman /><ref name="Ward">{{cite book|last=Ward|first=L|title=An explorer's guide to the Field Museum|year=1998|publisher=The Field Museum|location=Chicago}}</ref> The Field Museum is part of Chicago’s lakefront [[Museum Campus]] that includes the [[John G. Shedd Aquarium]] and the [[Adler Planetarium]].<ref name=MIP />
In 2015, it became public that an employee had defrauded the museum of $900,000 over a seven-year period to 2014.<ref name="ct">{{Cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/museums/ct-field-museum-employee-theft-20151211-story.html |title=Former Field Museum employee accused of stealing $900,000 over 7 years |last=Steve Johnson |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |publication-date=11 December 2015}}</ref> [[File:Annual report of the Director to the Board of Trustees for the year ... (1894) (17811373403).jpg|thumb|right|North Hall, circa 1895]] [[File:Field fg03.jpg|thumb|Main Hall]] [[File:Lionsoftsavo2008.jpg|thumb|The [[Tsavo Maneaters]] on display in Mammals of Africa exhibit hall]]
