'''Gro Steinsland''' (born 1945) is a Norwegian scholar of [[medieval studies]] and [[history of religion]] and since August 2009 has been the Scientific Director of the Centre for Advanced Study at the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]. 

Steinsland has most recently been a professor in the Institute for Linguistic and [[Scandinavian studies|Nordic Studies]] at the [[University of Oslo]], where she was also a member of the international interdepartmental Centre for Studies in the [[Viking Age]] and Nordic [[Middle Ages]]<ref name=forskning>[http://www.forskning.no/32/59 profile] at forskning.no {{no icon}}</ref><ref name=Apollon>Aslaug Veum, [http://www.apollon.uio.no/vis/art/1998/4/veithonok "Gro Steinsland: Veit ho nok, eller kva?"], Portrait, ''Apollon'', University of Oslo research magazine, 1 April 1998, retrieved 17 January 2011 {{nn icon}}</ref> from its founding in 1993 until its dissolution.<ref name=PROSA>Gunnhild Røthe, [http://www.prosa.no/artikkel.asp?ID=545 "Vet dere nok eller hva? Om den moderne volven Gro Steinslands forfatterskap"], Minibiografi, ''Prosa'' May 2009, retrieved 16 January 2011 {{no icon}}</ref> She has also taught in the Institute for Religious Studies at the [[University of Tromsø]] and has held guest faculty positions at [[Linacre College]], [[Oxford University]] and at the [[University of Bonn]].<ref name=forskning/> In 2007/08 she led the international interdisciplinary research group in "The Power of the Ruler and the Ideology of Rulership in Nordic Culture 800-1200" at the Centre for Advanced Study of the Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters,<ref>Olaf Christensen, [https://www.hf.uio.no/for-ansatte/aktuelt/hf-aktuelt/2005/uke47/steinsland.html HF-aktuelt: En fremragende religionshistoriker], Det humanistiske fakultet, University of Oslo, 21 November 2005, retrieved 17 January 2011 {{no icon}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cas.uio.no/research/0708rulership/index.php Research Group 2007/2008 - Rulership], Centre for Advanced Study, Oslo.</ref> and since 1 August 2009 has been its Scientific Director.<ref>Bjarne Røsjø and Else Lie, [http://www.forskningsradet.no/en/Newsarticle/Cultivating+the+crme+de+la+crme+of+basic+research/1253954293454&kilde=f "Centre for Advanced Study: Cultivating the crème de la crème of basic research"], Research Council of Norway, 4 March 2010, retrieved 14 January 2011.</ref>

Steinsland specialises in [[Germanic paganism|pre-Christian religion]], the associated [[Old Norse]] texts and [[mythology]] and the [[Christianization|conversion]] of Scandinavia.<ref name=forskning/> At both Oslo and Tromsø, she made Norse religion a main subject within the history of religion programme.<ref name=Apollon/> She is a member of the group for theology and religious studies in the Academy of Science and Letters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnva.no/c26848/artikkel/vis.html?tid=27645|title=Gruppe 8: Religionsvitenskap og teologi|publisher=[[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=15 January 2011}}</ref> As a historian of religion, her publications take [[Norsemen|Norse]] paganism seriously and present it in a non-traditional light as having been still strong and vital when it encountered Christianity.<ref name=PROSA/> In 2005 she published a wideranging introductory book, ''Norrøn religion'' (Norse religion), which presents the subject from the perspective of myth and praxis. In her influential 1989 [[PhD]] dissertation, ''Det hellige bryllup og norrøn kongeideologi: en analyse av hierogami-myten i Skírnismál, Ynglingatal, Háleygjatal og Hyndluljód'' (the [[sacred marriage]] and Norse ideology of kingship: an analysis of the myth of the ''hieros gamos'' in ''[[Skírnismál]]'', ''[[Ynglingatal]]'', ''[[Háleygjatal]]'' and ''[[Hyndluljóð]]''), she reinterpreted the sacred marriage between a god and a [[jötunn|giantess]] as a power [[myth]] legitimising rulership rather than a fertility myth; she specialises in the interpretation of written sources but has also made extensive use of [[archaeology]] and frequently takes an interdisciplinary approach.<ref name=PROSA/> She has also emphasised the female aspect of pre-Christian religion,<ref name=Apollon/> particularly in her 1997 book ''Eros og død i norrøne myter'' ([[Eros (concept)|Eros]] and death in Norse myths), in which she contrasts the sexualisation of death in, for example, references to drowning as being embraced by the sea goddess [[Rán]] with the post-conversion view of female sexuality as shameful.<ref name=PROSA/>

Steinsland has also readily written [[Op-ed|newspaper opinion article]]s,<ref name=forskning/> for example in 2000 taking the position that [[Thor Heyerdahl]]'s [[Odin]] expedition to [[Azerbaijan]] was a "charade" orchestrated by [[Snorri Sturluson]].<ref>[http://tux1.aftenposten.no/meninger/kronikker/d176403.htm "Heyerdahls og Odins 'narrespill': Med Thor Heyerdahls nye Odin-prosjekt er et 800 år gammelt 'narrespill' satt i scene, en gedigen skøyerstrek, regissert av Snorre Sturlason"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716233921/http://tux1.aftenposten.no/meninger/kronikker/d176403.htm |date=2011-07-16 }}, Meninger - Kronikk, ''Aftenposten'' 24 November 2000, retrieved January 14, 2011 {{no icon}}.</ref>

